WEBVTT

00:00:00.020 --> 00:00:00.640
Hello?

00:00:01.130 --> 00:00:01.460
Okay.

00:00:01.460 --> 00:00:03.440
My name is Chad Miller.

00:00:03.440 --> 00:00:07.500
You can find me on blue sky, chadcmiller

00:00:07.550 --> 00:00:07.710
.

00:00:07.710 --> 00:00:07.940
com.

00:00:07.950 --> 00:00:12.220
I've been doing a lot of different experimentation with app views

00:00:12.290 --> 00:00:12.580
.

00:00:12.770 --> 00:00:17.450
So a lot of experiments with apps that aren't blue sky

00:00:17.450 --> 00:00:20.580
clients or anything related to blue sky at all.

00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:23.310
Just kind of like you have some custom lexicons and

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:24.940
you want to build an app.

00:00:24.940 --> 00:00:29.680
So I've been doing a lot of experiments with that.

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:30.760
What is an app view?

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:34.480
If you don't know, it kind of sits in between

00:00:34.490 --> 00:00:38.760
the relay and the sort of client that you're using.

00:00:38.870 --> 00:00:43.570
So you have all this information flowing from all of your records

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:47.410
flowing from the PDS through the relay.

00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:50.910
The app view sort of is the place that stores all of

00:00:50.910 --> 00:00:54.470
your records and brings them all together from all the different PD

00:00:54.470 --> 00:01:01.800
Ss across the network and then sort of hydrate,

00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:03.700
brings all that data together, hydrates it.

00:01:03.710 --> 00:01:08.390
So you're like counts and your common counts and all that

00:01:08.600 --> 00:01:12.200
stuff and provides it to, you know, your web app

00:01:12.410 --> 00:01:16.660
or your mobile application to render it on the screen.

00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:22.060
If we look closer at the app view itself, there's

00:01:22.060 --> 00:01:24.080
a bunch of things going on.

00:01:24.260 --> 00:01:29.180
So we have a firehose connection, but we also

00:01:29.180 --> 00:01:32.520
need to take into account pretty much all the data that we

00:01:32.520 --> 00:01:33.180
care about.

00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:35.260
So the backfill, that's the backfill portion.

00:01:35.270 --> 00:01:39.530
So we have some kind of indexer that's going to

00:01:39.530 --> 00:01:42.900
take in all of these events from the network.

00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:45.210
You have like commit, commits.

00:01:45.410 --> 00:01:47.360
They're called commit events.

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:50.020
So you have creates, updates, deletes.

00:01:50.020 --> 00:01:53.850
Those then, you know, you filter those down to what

00:01:53.990 --> 00:01:54.670
you care about.

00:01:54.670 --> 00:01:59.480
So you might only care about a, what is the connection

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:06.520
lexicon from the connection app that everybody's been using

00:02:06.520 --> 00:02:06.870
.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:09.250
You might only care about that.

00:02:09.250 --> 00:02:11.940
So that filters through the database and then you sort of have

00:02:11.940 --> 00:02:17.870
a hydration layer that's going to request all those and return

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:22.190
them via what in at protoland is called XRPC

00:02:22.190 --> 00:02:23.380
endpoints.

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:26.380
Really, it's just an HTTP endpoint that's typed against

00:02:26.450 --> 00:02:27.460
your lexicons.

00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:30.690
So you can define what the responses are in your lex

00:02:30.690 --> 00:02:31.930
icon definitions.

00:02:32.030 --> 00:02:35.170
And then if we look a little bit closer at the sort

00:02:35.170 --> 00:02:40.570
of request pipeline, you'll, if you look closer at

00:02:40.670 --> 00:02:43.850
the app proto repo, you'll sort of see this pattern

00:02:43.850 --> 00:02:44.270
a lot.

00:02:44.530 --> 00:02:47.860
And you sort of fetch all of the, you know,

00:02:47.870 --> 00:02:51.480
you batch fetch all these records from the database, apply some

00:02:51.730 --> 00:02:52.730
rules to them.

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:58.710
This might be some labels that you have for moderation.

00:02:59.020 --> 00:03:02.100
And, you know, bringing all that together, all of

00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:06.160
the, the like counts and the common counts together to return

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:07.780
the JSON response.

00:03:07.790 --> 00:03:13.190
So where can you get started if you want to build your

00:03:13.190 --> 00:03:14.810
own app view?

00:03:14.930 --> 00:03:19.820
You know, the main reference repo is the app proto repo

00:03:19.820 --> 00:03:23.620
that is essentially the backend for blue sky.

00:03:23.620 --> 00:03:27.290
How many people have spent a lot of time digging through that

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:27.620
code?

00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:29.140
Yeah.

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:34.630
There's status sphere, but it's pretty basic.

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:36.750
It just has like a single crud, it's just

00:03:36.760 --> 00:03:38.150
like a create operation.

00:03:38.150 --> 00:03:41.570
So it's not really like that much going on.

00:03:41.590 --> 00:03:44.300
And obviously you want your app to be a lot more,

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:47.380
you know, a lot richer than status sphere.

00:03:47.390 --> 00:03:50.890
And then we have all the community app views.

00:03:50.890 --> 00:03:53.460
So we have like leaflet, tangled.

00:03:53.480 --> 00:03:56.080
What else is there?

00:03:56.260 --> 00:03:58.660
Margin.

00:03:58.660 --> 00:04:00.660
There's off print.

00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:02.740
There's all these app views out there now.

00:04:02.750 --> 00:04:07.110
So there's a lot of good reference places, like depending

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:09.540
on which programming language you're into.

00:04:11.230 --> 00:04:13.050
And right now it's kind of like, you know,

00:04:13.050 --> 00:04:13.840
an art project.

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:17.780
So everybody has their own implementation of what, you know,

00:04:17.780 --> 00:04:18.890
it says on app proto.

00:04:18.890 --> 00:04:21.740
com and the specs and what they've sort of gathered from

00:04:21.780 --> 00:04:22.740
the app proto repo.

00:04:22.750 --> 00:04:29.930
I have spent some time sort of putting patterns together into a

00:04:29.930 --> 00:04:33.450
service that you can just deploy called quick slice.

00:04:33.460 --> 00:04:37.280
And it sort of maps your lexicons to a Graph

00:04:37.280 --> 00:04:41.390
QL API that you can just query without having to do a

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:43.380
whole lot.

00:04:43.390 --> 00:04:45.780
And then there's also constellation.

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:48.020
There's sometimes you might not need an app view.

00:04:48.020 --> 00:04:53.220
So figs APIs provide a way to just get like,

00:04:53.220 --> 00:04:55.820
like, for example, npmx just wants to show

00:04:55.870 --> 00:05:00.130
the like count on their packages.

00:05:00.250 --> 00:05:02.330
So they can just use constellation for that.

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:03.460
So they don't even need nep view.

00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:06.440
So what are all the things that you need?

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:10.020
You need a way to backfill all the data on the

00:05:10.130 --> 00:05:10.420
network.

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:15.060
So that is going to be probably heard a lot about tap

00:05:15.060 --> 00:05:15.060
.

00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:20.680
Tap provides a way to to filter those collections that you want

00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:20.890
.

00:05:23.390 --> 00:05:26.630
There's also other ways you can parse the card files manually

00:05:26.630 --> 00:05:28.580
and have your own process for backfilling.

00:05:28.590 --> 00:05:31.460
Indexing.

00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:35.400
So you need some sort of layer to translate the lex

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:39.540
icon records into your database.

00:05:39.550 --> 00:05:45.650
And then there's some kind of code gen aspect, which

00:05:45.650 --> 00:05:47.780
works with the lexicon definitions.

00:05:49.150 --> 00:05:50.950
Again, with the XRPC endpoints.

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:53.620
So usually when you're working with lexicons, you

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:56.910
want a way to have, you know, type safe end

00:05:56.910 --> 00:05:58.900
points against those.

00:05:58.910 --> 00:06:01.000
OAuth.

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:06.010
Generally be nice to have this all figured out for you and

00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:06.900
you don't have to worry about it.

00:06:06.910 --> 00:06:14.700
And not really necessary for every application, but there is this

00:06:14.700 --> 00:06:17.870
concept of the feed generator in blue sky, which is a

00:06:17.870 --> 00:06:23.550
separate server that you can run that pretty much just returns the

00:06:23.810 --> 00:06:27.600
URIs of records that can be picked up by blue

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:28.740
sky to render a feed.

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:34.500
That same pattern can be used in any app proto application.

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:36.670
And I'm actually going to show you really in a second

00:06:36.670 --> 00:06:38.830
what that looks like.

00:06:38.830 --> 00:06:40.820
Labels.

00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:42.880
Obviously, if you want to do some kind of moderation,

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:45.360
you're going to need to have some sort of support for

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:46.100
labeling.

00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:49.260
This can be a simple, just a simple table in your

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:52.370
database to make it quick.

00:06:52.460 --> 00:06:56.260
And then preferences.

00:06:56.270 --> 00:07:01.680
Sometimes you want to have data that's stored privately to the

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:03.050
app view.

00:07:03.050 --> 00:07:06.880
And you can sort of just have a preferences table for that

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:07.140
.

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:10.340
And then open graph.

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:14.370
So generally you want to have a way to like share images

00:07:14.370 --> 00:07:19.770
, image previews back to blue sky for for rendering like

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:21.460
a social post.

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:26.030
So I've been sort of playing around with the newer ideas

00:07:26.030 --> 00:07:28.610
in this framework I call hack.

00:07:28.610 --> 00:07:32.330
It's sort of like a conventional, like a convention over

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:37.910
configuration, although there's still some configuration framework for building an

00:07:37.910 --> 00:07:39.050
app view.

00:07:39.050 --> 00:07:44.470
You can sort of attach this app view server to a S

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:44.980
velte app.

00:07:46.750 --> 00:07:48.150
You can check it out at hack.

00:07:48.150 --> 00:07:48.490
dev.

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:49.860
It's pretty early alpha.

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:51.860
Just sort of playing around with some ideas.

00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:56.870
I just recently rewrote grain social to use -- this

00:07:56.940 --> 00:08:01.220
is the -- rewrote grain social to use all these

00:08:01.340 --> 00:08:02.160
patterns.

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:04.660
It's all open source untangled.

00:08:04.660 --> 00:08:06.660
There's a bunch of feeds here.

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:13.100
People upload photos and it shows the data as a feed and

00:08:13.430 --> 00:08:14.740
locations as a feed.

00:08:14.740 --> 00:08:20.130
And then there's actually one thing I wanted to point out

00:08:20.130 --> 00:08:23.820
is there's a great pattern for running your app view locally

00:08:23.860 --> 00:08:24.080
.

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:27.160
A lot of times it's hard to reproduce stuff because there

00:08:27.160 --> 00:08:28.360
's a lot, you know, there's a lot of

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:31.410
stuff that you have to do to bring an app view together

00:08:31.410 --> 00:08:31.610
.

00:08:31.610 --> 00:08:34.630
But there's a pattern in there for running your app locally

00:08:34.920 --> 00:08:39.730
and having reproducible data that you can use to help build

00:08:39.730 --> 00:08:40.860
your app.

00:08:41.480 --> 00:08:49.380
And yeah, that's all I got.
